Welfare is the providing of help and assistance to needy people and families. The following are examples of welfare programs and services: This comprises Temporary Help for Needy Families (TANF), which offers cash aid to low-income families with children, and Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program (SNAP), which provides food assistance to low-income people and families. This includes programs like as Medicaid, which provides low-income people and families with health care coverage, and the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP), which offers health care coverage to children from low-income households. This includes programs such as Section 8 housing vouchers and public housing, which offer low-income people and families with affordable accommodation. This includes programs like Head Start and Job Corps, which give education and skills to low-income youngsters. This includes programs like as Social Security and Supplemental Security Income (SSI), which offer financial help to retired, handicapped, or otherwise unable-to-work persons. These are a few examples of welfare programs; however, welfare laws and services may vary from nation to country and can also include unemployment benefits, pension benefits, and disability benefits, among others. 